narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I learned how to study efficiently and manage time.
Through this class I was able to develop a very strong foundation of various mathematical skills and learn various concepts thoroughly.
I developed a stronger understanding of calculus and a deeper ability to think logically. I also feel that I've become better at spatial reasoning.
Calculus BC and critical thinking skills.

I learned about estimating areas through Riemann sums, integration and varying techniques, series and sequences, calculating volumes of solids, and parametric curves. By exploring these diverse, yet related mathematical concepts, I was able to think critically and creatively and apply my knowledge from class in a concrete, tangible way through practice problems.
I learned how to do intergals.
I learned how to more critically think about math in a more conceptual manner and build upon my previous knowledge of calculus.
Integral calculus, study skills, collaboration on psets

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: I enjoyed the way the teacher taught and the manner in which the content was presented. Very easy to follow and learn.

Some strengths include allowing students to develop thorough explanations of various concepts that help students build a strong understanding of topics besides just making them memorize equations. 
No significant weaknesses in this course, though I would have benefitted from direct examples that come after learning a new formula or concept so I can have a better grasp on how to apply new concepts.
This course is well planned. There are multiple systems of support. I would make the homeworks more useful. I thought the explores were not that helpful.
My instructor was a strength in this course. Also, I really love how it was structured and spread out when it came to assignments so that we had time to complete psets.

strengths: extremely(!!!!!) well organized and well-paced, abundance of resources (practice review problems, problem sets, past midterm and final exams), pre-class questions (encouraged us to learn content before class and build on/clarify learning during class), learning strategies (helped a lot in keeping me organized especially for exams and thinking ahead!! would not have survived without this), explorations provided tangilble real-world application of calculus
weaknesses: none
Very good and well paced classes with helpful hand outs which walk you through the topics nicely

I personally did not find the Exploration Tasks to be helpful, but rather a bit time-consuming and challenging. I believe replacing these would be beneficial. One useful component of this class was the availability of peer tutoring hours, which fell on most days of the week.

This course is very well organized, and the instructors have created an engaging curriculum and positive class environment. The psets are manageable. It is difficult to force myself to stay invested, however, as the class does not check-in often with its students or demand too much attention.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes because the instructor is really good and the class builds on bigger concepts in Calculus, that in my opinion was a lot easier to grasp and understand than Calc 1.
Yes, it would help them build fundamental mathematical skills that would provide good foundation for any math classes in the future.
Yes. I felt that it left me well-prepared for any classes I might take in the future requiring knowledge of calculus.
Yes! I loved this course. It has inspired me to continue on my math career at Yale.

Yes, I would recommend this course to another student! It is better than Math 112 in my opinion and has more interesting types of problems and it is easier to see the real world applications of many of these topics. I loved taking it with Rachel  while challenging, it is incredibly well-taught, well-resourced, and well-organized. You will develop sharper critical and creative thinking skills after having taken the course and there is a robust support system available for you in case you are struggling, which you will experience at some point. Just make sure to review often and do a bunch of practice to do well!
Good course that teaches you a lot of key math elements. If you can get Rachel Diethorn then I would definitely recommend she is an amazing professor

I would recommend this course to another student because I personally found it very useful to take immediately after MATH 112. I learned a lot of calculus in this class, although it was challenging at times.
Only if you have to take it for a major requirement.
